Scientific Literature Review: Structures and Best Practices
Choosing the Right Review Type First
The structure flows directly from the review's purpose, so this decision comes first. A systematic review applies a predefined, reproducible search protocol with formal quality appraisal - appropriate when you need a defensible, auditable evidence base (regulatory submissions, EFSA-style weight-of-evidence assessments). A narrative review offers more interpretive flexibility and is better suited to broad conceptual synthesis or emerging fields with limited primary data. A scoping review maps the literature landscape without formal quality weighting - useful for identifying data gaps before a full systematic review. A meta-analysis is a systematic review with quantitative pooling of effect sizes, requiring sufficient homogeneity across studies to be meaningful.

For most regulatory science contexts, systematic or semi-systematic approaches are expected and increasingly mandated.

Core Structure
Introduction should establish the rationale concisely: what question is being addressed, why it matters, and what gap exists in current knowledge. The scope and objectives need to be stated explicitly, not implied.

Methods is where rigour lives. Define your search strategy (databases searched, date ranges, search terms and Boolean logic), inclusion/exclusion criteria applied a priori, and the data extraction approach. If you're doing a systematic review, register the protocol on PROSPERO before you start - this prevents post-hoc criterion shifting and is increasingly expected by high-impact journals. Document every step so the review is reproducible by an independent reviewer.

Results should present the evidence objectively, organised by theme or endpoint rather than source-by-source. A PRISMA flow diagram is standard for systematic reviews to show the screening cascade. Evidence tables (structured summaries of study design, species/endpoint, effect levels, data quality) are far more useful than prose-only summaries and make QA straightforward.

Synthesis and Discussion is where you move from description to interpretation. Critically evaluate consistency across studies, address heterogeneity and conflicting data explicitly, assess methodological quality, and frame a weight-of-evidence conclusion. Do not bury contradictory findings or treat all studies as equally weighted - this is where many regulatory reviews fall short.

Conclusions should directly answer the original objectives. Be precise about what the evidence supports versus what remains uncertain or unresolved, and identify data gaps that warrant further investigation.

Best Practices That Actually Distinguish Good Reviews
Search comprehensiveness. Use at least three independent databases (PubMed/MEDLINE, Web of Science, Scopus as a minimum), plus grey literature sources appropriate to your field. For regulatory science this means EFSA Journal, ECHA CHEM, national competent authority outputs, and unpublished study reports if accessible. Relying solely on one database introduces systematic bias.

Predefined criteria. Inclusion/exclusion criteria must be defined before screening begins, not tuned to the literature you happen to find. Document any deviations.

Dual independent screening. For systematic reviews, at least two reviewers should screen titles/abstracts and full texts independently, with disagreements resolved by a third reviewer or consensus discussion. Inter-rater reliability (Cohen's kappa) should be reported.

Critical appraisal. Every included study should be assessed for methodological quality and risk of bias. Validated tools exist for this: CAMARADES for animal studies, Cochrane RoB 2 for RCTs, OHAT for hazard identification. In ecotoxicology, study quality frameworks like ToxRTool or Klimisch scoring are common. The EFSA guidance on systematic reviews in food/feed safety (2010, updated 2022) provides a robust framework directly applicable to PPP work.

Transparent handling of heterogeneity. When studies conflict, the discussion needs to explain why - differences in species sensitivity, study design, exposure routes, test conditions - rather than dismissing outliers or averaging across incomparable datasets.

Living reviews where appropriate. For fast-moving fields, a structured update protocol with a defined review cycle is worth building in from the start.

Reporting Standards
PRISMA 2020 is the benchmark reporting guideline for systematic reviews and meta-analyses, with domain-specific extensions (PRISMA-EcoEvo for ecological studies, for example). SWiM (Synthesis Without Meta-analysis) covers narrative synthesis of quantitative studies where pooling is inappropriate. Whichever you use, adherence to the relevant reporting standard should be stated explicitly in the methods.

A well-structured evidence table and a clear PRISMA flow diagram will do more for the defensibility of a regulatory review than most methodological refinements elsewhere in the document.

