Here are the three report structures as working templates, with section headings, content descriptors, and mandatory/recommended status.



Section titles are written as direct headings - copy-paste ready. A few structural points worth noting:

The quick review's Section 1.3 (Scope and constraints) and Section 5 (Limitations) are the paired integrity mechanism: one defines what the review covers, the other states what that means for the conclusions. Separating them into distinct sections rather than folding them into the discussion forces explicit treatment of both.

The comparative model's Section 3 is intentionally the heaviest part of the document. The cross-arm synthesis in Section 4 should not repeat what was already reported per arm - it synthesises across them. Section 4.4 (Incomparable domains) is frequently omitted in practice and should not be. If two evidence bases cannot be directly compared due to methodological heterogeneity, that finding belongs in the report as a standalone conclusion.

